# Shell scripts must stay LF regardless of platform — CRLF makes bash die with
# `$'\r': command not found` (bit the LAN dry-run + the WSL build env repeatedly).
*.sh   text eol=lf
*.bash text eol=lf
# .sh.example templates get copied to hosts verbatim — same CRLF hazard
# (ktp-scheduled-restart.sh.example sat CRLF in the repo until 2026-07-07).
*.sh.example text eol=lf
# .conf.example files are `source`d by bash after copying — a CRLF value makes
# LAN_IP="" parse as the 1-char value \r and PASS the required-key check
# (lan-deploy.conf.example sat CRLF in the working tree until 2026-07-07).
*.conf.example text eol=lf
# Everything below deploys verbatim to Linux hosts (SFTP copies bytes as-is):
# a fresh Windows clone without these rules materializes CRLF, and a deploy
# then ships \r into systemd unit parsing / python shebangs / ini values.
*.py         text eol=lf
*.py.example text eol=lf
*.service    text eol=lf
*.ini        text eol=lf
*.ini.example text eol=lf
*.j2         text eol=lf
*.cron       text eol=lf
